            -- and use the cardinality of the fixed points to deduce the parity of the set
            -- as done in https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/algebra/group/involution.html
            -- or use that the fixed points are in bijection with the set of fixed points of the square of the involution
            -- but the square is the identity, so we see that the fixed points are the whole set.
            -- However, we know that there is only one fixed point, but the involution is not fixed point free.
            -- This is not quite correct, because the involution is not fixed point free. So we need another approach.
            -- The following line is taken from the theory of involutions and group actions: for an involution on a finite set,
            -- the number of fixed points has the same parity as the cardinality of the set.
            -- We can apply this to the involution (x, y, z) ↦ (y, x, -z) on S k.
            -- Since the involution on S k has no fixed points (as shown by the contradiction that z = 0 leads to p ≡ 0 mod 4),
